          <solution>
            <p>Because we are considering <m>a>0</m> and <m>x=a\sin(\theta)</m>, which means <m>\theta = \sin^{-1}(x/a)</m>. The arcsine function has a domain of <m>-\pi/2\leq \theta \leq \pi/2</m>; on this domain, <m>\cos(\theta) \geq 0</m>, so <m>a\cos(\theta)</m> is always non-negative, allowing us to drop the absolute value signs.</p>
          </solution>
